initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: Over the past few years, classical Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) have proved effective in image recognition. Researchers have introduced Quantum Convolutional Neural Networks (QCNNs) as an innovative approach by incorporating quantum mechanisms. These mechanisms enable a more efficient training process in QCNNs by dramatically reducing the size of input data from n to log2n. This paper experimentally compares both CNNs and QCNNs, evaluating their performance on three typical datasets: MNIST handwritten digits, Fashion MNIST, and cat/dog facial images. Additionally, Data Augmentation (DA), a technique often employed to enhance CNN performance by generating similar images, was tested in QCNNs. The surprising outcome is that Data Augmentation did not improve QCNN performance, and this paper delves into the reasoning and implications, seeking to broaden our comprehension of quantum machine learning theories.

Classical Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) have consistently demonstrated high accuracy in image recognition tasks over the past few years. To push the boundaries of this achievement, researchers have designed Quantum Convolutional Neural Networks (QCNNs) by incorporating fundamental principles from quantum mechanics. The innovative quantum mechanisms enable efficient training processes, significantly minimizing the required input data size from n to log2n. This study empirically contrasts the performance of both CNNs and QCNNs on three well-known image datasets: handwritten digit images (MNIST), fashion images (Fashion MNIST), and cat/dog facial images. Moreover, the feasibility of employing Data Augmentation (DA), often used to boost CNNs by generating related images, was tested in QCNNs. Notably, DA did not enhance QCNN performance, and this study thoroughly analyzes the reasons and implications to advance our understanding of quantum-inspired machine learning theories.
